Figure 4A shows RMSDs for the DDM with a simulated difficulty (Study 2) and speed-vs-accuracy manipulation (Study 3) for different error rates and trial numbers. As in Study 1, RMSDs of a and v are higher for decreasing error rates and for 150 (Study 2) and 200 (Study 3) compared to 1200 trials. RMSDs are also higher for drift rates estimated for conditions with lower difficulty (as these have a lower error rate) and similar to RMSDs for drift rates in Study 1 with a comparable error rate of 5%. RMSDs for decision thresholds are similar in accuracy and speed conditions. Interestingly, RMSDs for decision thresholds and drift rates are overall lower for the speed-vs-accuracy manipulation than for the difficulty manipulation. They are also lower than RMSDs for decision thresholds in Study 1 with a comparable error rate of 5%. This is true even for \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$a_{acc}$$\end{document}aacc in the accuracy condition which was estimated with a lower error rate and smaller trial number than a in the difficulty manipulation.

